+Add a middleware system that can intercept and transform tasks as they are processed.
 
 ## Requirements
 
-- Middleware functions run in the order they were added (first added = first to run)
-- Each middleware must call `next()` to pass control to the next middleware (and eventually the handler)
-- If a middleware does NOT call `next()`, the task processing is skipped
-- Middleware can modify the task object (e.g., add metadata)
-- If a middleware throws an error, the task is marked as failed
-- Each queue has its own independent middleware stack
-- Middleware receives the full task context (task object)
-- `process()` dequeues a task and runs it through the middleware pipeline, then the handler
+- Middleware functions can be registered per queue.
+- When a task is processed, it passes through all registered middleware in order before reaching the final handler.
+- Each middleware receives the task and a "next" function. Calling "next" passes control to the next middleware (or the handler).
+- If a middleware does NOT call "next", the task processing is skipped.
+- Middleware can modify the task (e.g., adding metadata or transforming the payload).
+- If a middleware throws an error, the task should be marked as failed.
+- A processing function/handler can be registered per queue. It is invoked after all middleware have run.
+- Each queue has its own independent middleware stack.
